    "body": "### Description\n\nThe documented `on_attach` setting for the `eslint` language server fails for me on the following error:\n```\nError detected while processing /home/ross/projects/personal/dotfiles/nvim/.config/nvim/init.lua:\nE5113: Error while calling lua chunk: /home/ross/.config/nvim/lua/configuration/lspconfig.lua:14: attempt to index field 'eslint' (a nil value)\nstack traceback:\n        /home/ross/.config/nvim/lua/configuration/lspconfig.lua:14: in main chunk\n        [C]: in function 'require'\n        /home/ross/.config/nvim/lua/configuration/init.lua:1: in main chunk\n        [C]: in function 'require'\n```\n\nDocumented setup:\n```\nThe default `on_attach` config provides the `LspEslintFixAll` command that can be used to format a document on save >lua\n  local base_on_attach = vim.lsp.config.eslint.on_attach\n  vim.lsp.config(\"eslint\", {\n    on_attach = function(client, bufnr)\n      if not base_on_attach then return end\n\n      base_on_attach(client, bufnr)\n      vim.api.nvim_create_autocmd(\"BufWritePre\", {\n        buffer = bufnr,\n        command = \"LspEslintFixAll\",\n      })\n    end,\n  })\n```\n\nMy setup:\n\n```lua\nlocal base_on_attach = vim.lsp.config.eslint.on_attach -- fails on this line\n\nlocal servers = {\n  -- ...\n  eslint = {\n    on_attach = function(client, bufnr)\n      if not base_on_attach then return end\n\n      base_on_attach(client, bufnr)\n      vim.api.nvim_create_autocmd(\"BufWritePre\", {\n        buffer = bufnr,\n        command = \"LspEslintFixAll\",\n      })\n    end,\n  },\n-- ...\n\nfor server, config in pairs(servers) do\n  vim.lsp.config(server, config)\n  vim.lsp.enable(server)\nend\n```\n\nVim version (Issue was also present on v0.11.1):\n```\nNVIM v0.11.3\nBuild type: Release\nLuaJIT 2.1.1741730670\n```\n\nLspconfig version (from Lazy package manager lock file):\n```\n  \"nvim-lspconfig\": { \"branch\": \"master\", \"commit\": \"77d3fdfb3554632c7a3b101ded643d422de7626f\" },\n``` \n\nI'm trying to move to the `vim.lsp` APIs rather than `require('lspconfig')` but this issue prevents me from making the move. Any help appreciated.",
